Actually, looking at the evalite source code more carefully:
```js
it.concurrent(fullEvalName, async ({ task, annotate }) => {
    if (!annotate || typeof annotate !== "function") {
        throw new Error("Evalite requires Vitest 3.2.4 or later for the annotations API. Please upgrade: `npm install vitest@latest`");
    }
```

This validates that the `annotate` function exists and is callable. If vitest 4.x changed how this API works, it would fail the check and mark the eval as failed rather than showing 0ms with no score. So the issue must be elsewhere—probably in how the results are being rendered when scores are missing.

